The original 1972 Holiday Isle recipe contained no fruit juices — it relied on Rose's lime and grenadine alone for tartness and color, with modern orange-and-pineapple variants being a later evolution. Historical accounts also vary on the rum: this spec uses 1 oz Myers's dark, while Tiki John's original called for 0.75 oz Bacardi 151. The blackberry brandy and banana liqueur are the load-bearing flavor backbone.

In a #blender{} or #shaker{} combine @Myers's dark rum{1%oz}, @blackberry brandy{1%oz} (or crème de mûre), @banana liqueur{1%oz}, @Rose's lime juice{0.75%oz}, and @Rose's grenadine{0.75%oz}.

Blend with @crushed ice{1%cup} until slushy (the original was served frozen) or shake with ice and strain over @crushed ice{} in a #hurricane glass{}.

Garnish with an @orange slice{1} and a @maraschino cherry{1}.
